Greenland shark: The oldest vertebrate is almost 400 years old
A rare sight.
Greenland sharks usually come to the surface only in winter.
The shark was allowed to return to the sea on board the research ship Sanna.
He was born in 1624 and swims at about 1 km/h through the North Atlantic - to this day.
Greenland sharks only get offspring at 150 years old.
The Greenland shark swims at the bottom of the North Atlantic Ocean, reaching an average of 1,220 meters in an hour.
Only when it comes to it, the five-meter-long animal accelerates to just 2.6 km/h - and at this maximum speed is half as fast as a barley.
However, this lifestyle characterized by slowness seems to be a pattern recipe for old age.
Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the journal "Science" at least of a Greenland shark that could be 392 years old.
“Crazy,” Alexander Scheuerlein of the Max Planck Institute for Demographic Research in Rostock commented on this lifespan, which is a world record for vertebrates.
Evolutionary biologists have long suspected that Greenland sharks are stoning.
Only the evidence was lacking.
Greenland sharks are difficult to observe, after all, they live mainly in the Ice Sea off the thinly populated coasts of Canada, Greenland, Norway and Spitzbergen.
Because they prefer water temperatures of around six degrees Celsius, they usually only appear on the surface in the winter.
Researchers know very little about the lifestyle of Greenland sharks.
They measured their pace of time when they equipped six animals with a transmitter in front of Spitzbergen.
Sacrifice does these sharks do anyway: in the stomach of one animal, researchers found the remains of a frog, another had swallowed the jaw bone of a young icy bear.
They may be hunting for sleeping animals or patroling at the bottom of the ice lake, looking for corpses that torch down from higher layers of water.
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues now studied 28 Greenland sharks that fishermen caught from the depths of the North Atlantic between 2010 and 2013 outside Greenland or Spitzbergen.
The smallest shark was just 81 centimeters in length, while the largest was 502 centimeters.
To determine the age of the animals, they analyzed the shark lens nucleus using the carbon-14 method.
This center of the eye lens is formed before the sharks are born, the proteins contained therein are no longer renewed later.
The two smallest sharks had a striking amount of carbon-14 in the lens core.
Their birth was therefore supposed to be after the early 1960s, when nuclear weapons tests dumped larger amounts of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere.
In contrast, in the third smallest animal with 220 centimeters in length, the lens core contained a small surplus of carbon-14 from nuclear weapons tests, which is believed to have celebrated its 50th birthday when it was investigated in 2012.
All larger Greenland sharks, on the other hand, had normal amounts of carbon-14 in their lens core, which is generated by cosmic radiation in the atmosphere.
In fact, the carbon-14 clock for a 493-centimeter-long Greenland shark showed a age of 335 years, while the record shark with 502-centimeters is likely to be 392 years old.
It was known that female Greenland sharks only get offspring when they are longer than four meters.
Now, the researchers were able to assign an age to the length.
Since one of the animals, 392 centimeters tall, was probably on the threshold of sexual maturity and its age was determined at 156 years, Greenland sharks seem to be able to reproduce for at least one and a half centuries.
This is currently a world record for vertebrates.
That such methals live mainly in icy waters is no coincidence.
The previous record holder, a 211 year old Greenland whale with a 120 year old harpun spike on its neck, was also caught outside of Alaska.
Due to the low temperatures, the organism of the animals living there often runs on fire.
They mature later – and age more slowly.
In order to stay warm in the cold water, the animals also often become especially large.
Because the volume grows much faster than its surface, through which the animal loses heat.
Therefore, the heat loss of a gram of mouse is much greater than that of an elephant.
Another advantage is that you have fewer enemies.
"Therefore, a smaller animal lives more dangerously and should focus on having as many offspring as possible as soon as possible," explains evolutionary biologist Scheuerlein.
A very large animal, on the other hand, should rather invest its resources in a long life.
