Kepler measures the rotation rate of stars in the Pleiades star cluster
The latest mission with the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers gather the most comprehensive catalog of rotation rates among the stars of the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in the star cluster rotate at different rates and how rotation periods are related to planet formation.
“We hope that by comparing our findings with other star clusters, we can learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age, and even the history of its solar system,” said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech’s Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena.
The Pleiades star cluster is 445 light-years away from Earth.
Many stars in this star cluster, which formed about 125 million years ago, are now reaching adulthood.
They are turning the fastest.
At peak rotation rates, these mature stars emit large amounts of star winds.
As these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a braking effect on the stars.
As a star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by detecting the time between the appearance of a recognizable star spot, such as a solar spot.
The latest catalogue of rotation rates suggests that more massive stars rotate slower than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, with larger stars rotating slow pirouettes than smaller ones.
“In the ‘ballet’ of the Pleiades, we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, while faster rotors tend to be very bright stars,” Rebull said.
Because the star cluster is so close to the Pleiades, it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory to compare stellar qualities such as rotation rates.
"The Pleiadian star cluster provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older," Rebull said.
There is still a lot ahead of us that we would like to learn more about how, when, and why stars slow their rotation rates and so to speak, hang their “dance shoes.”
Rebull and her colleagues have detailed their latest analysis of the Pleiadian rotation rates in three newspapers that will soon appear in the Astronomical Journal.
