How hackers blackmail their ransom
Ransomware programmers are currently targeting – and are successfully doing so.
According to a recent survey by Malwarebytes malware defense specialists among 540 companies in North America, the UK and Germany, 40 percent of the companies surveyed have been victims of a ransomware attack at least once in the past 12 months.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of companies have already been the target of ransomware blackmail.
40% of the victims were willing to pay the ransom required by the perpetrators to reuse the systems and data attacked.
The perpetrators specialize in their ransomware, according to Malwarebytes’ observations, looking at attacks on corporate networks.
If they succeed there, the potentially blackmailed ransom will be significantly higher than for private users.
"We are currently witnessing a frighteningly rapid evolution of malware," Malwarebytes chief executive Marcin Kleczynski told The World.
In 2008, most malware programs were still designed to send advertisements.
Then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves.
At first, private users were the target, but the shift to corporate attacks took place frighteningly quickly in recent months.
Ransomware works in a simple pattern: Once active on a victim’s computer, it targetedly searches for recently modified files such as Word, Excel, or database files, as well as archives of images and videos.
These files encrypt the ransomware and delete the original permanently.
The software then presents the demands of the blackmailers.
In order to get the end-encryption code to the files, the victims will need to transfer money – mostly in the form of the cryptocurrency Bitcoin.
But where the personal photo database is at stake for private users, companies are talking about sensitive customer data or project databases, without which production stops.
Consequently, the damage will be higher if a ransomware attacks.
22% of German firms affected loss of revenue due to ransomware, 13% even had to completely discontinue business activities, in one case people were in danger.
In Germany, hospitals have already been victims of attacks several times, whose patients may be acutely threatened by the loss of medical records.
“We always say to the victims: don’t pay, you only promote the problem,” Kleczynski explains.
However, 80 to 90 percent of companies who pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to reject the demands of the perpetrators in the face of downtime in the operation.
The hackers, in turn, know this and try their best to build a good reputation.
In a recent study, F-Secure security researchers have examined the user interfaces and contact with the blackmailers and come to the conclusion that the perpetrators are actually trying to build a kind of customer service to get more money.
They explain to their victims via chat how to pay with Bitcoin, set up freely accessible support websites, or decrypt sample files for free.
And if individuals are redeemed after paying a few hundred euros, companies will have to negotiate hard and pay five-digit sums to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the potentially high and relatively risk-free profits from ransomware blackmail, hackers are becoming more and more professional and sharing the job, security expert Chester Wisniewski of antivirus provider Sophos explains: “A single person can write a ransomware about within a week.”
However, it is more likely that it is three or four people.
The programmers then sell their malicious software in the form of a software build-up to the actual blackmailers.
The previous malware kits were created by purchasing the malware itself, advice and additional tools for a one-time, fixed price between $1,000 and $10,000.
"A customization tool is included so that smaller configurations, appearance and branding can be changed," says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then search for other hackers to spread the newly purchased software among the victims.
We live in a service economy.
So you log in to one of the underground forums, buy the set from a criminal and commission another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
“Typically, the criminals then commission spammers to spread it,” explains Wisniewski.
The risk of ransomware is now known to many companies who better back up their data.
More than 50 percent of enterprise IT managers in the Malwarebytes survey trust to be able to counter ransomware using file backups and scanner software.
Therefore, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
“When data encryption alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful blackmail, the perpetrators are instead threatening to release sensitive data such as customer lists or price estimates,” said Marcin Kleczynski, CEO of Malwarebytes.
This means that the potential for damage depending on the type of data is still many times higher than before.
In the future, the perpetrators could also take on entirely new targets on the Internet of Things.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could get a thermostat connected to the Internet under their control.
In the middle of the winter, unlocking such a blocked heating system could be worth a ransom for so many victims.
If the perpetrators then block an entire manufacturing route in a factory instead of heating in the future, ransomware could also become a problem in Industry 4.0.
